Jelly tags {{jira:CreateProjectRole}} and {{jira:AddPermission}} use the following:

* {{jelly.role.id}} context variable which has *Long* type.
* {{projectroleid}} attribute which has *int* type.

If someone wants to create a new Project Role and then set the appropriate Permissions to this role, so he needs to pass the project role id to the {{jira:AddPermission}} tag.

If it is done like in this code snippet...

{code}
<JiraJelly xmlns:jira="jelly:com.atlassian.jira.jelly.JiraTagLib" xmlns:j="jelly:core">

<jira:CreateProjectRole name="Test1" description="A description">
${jelly.role.id} ${jelly.role.name} ${jelly.role.description}
</jira:CreateProjectRole>

<j:set var="BackV" value="${jelly.role.id}"/>

<jira:AddPermission schemeId="0" permissions="Edit" type="projectrole" projectroleid= "${BackV}"/>

</JiraJelly>
{code}

... the following error occurs:

{code}
org.apache.commons.jelly.JellyTagException: null:10:0: <jira:AddPermission> Cannot assign value of type 'java.lang.Long' to property 'projectroleid' of type 'java.lang.String'
{code}

The script can be fixed by replacing this line:

{code}
<j:set var="BackV" value="${jelly.role.id}"/>
{code}

with this:

{code}
<j:invoke on="${jelly.role.id}" method="toString" var="BackV"/>
{code}

This request is to change the tags, so they use the same types between corresponding variables/attributes. It would eliminate the need of converting values from one tag to another.

